(a) This question will resolve as Yes if, by January 1 following the next US presidential election, there is clear evidence that the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) new policies have significantly influenced the outcome of the presidential election. Significant influence is defined as a measurable impact on voter behavior, election results, or public opinion, directly attributable to the FDA's policies. This impact must be confirmed by at least three reputable sources (e.g., major news organizations like BBC, The New York Times, Washington Post, or academic studies). In the absence of direct evidence, a consensus among political analysts from at least three major news organizations or academic institutions that the FDA's policies played a critical role in the election outcome will also result in a Yes resolution. The resolution will consider only policies introduced before the election year.

(b) This question will resolve as Yes if, by December 31, 2025, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has published a comprehensive report on the health impacts of climate change. The report must cover a wide range of health impacts directly and indirectly related to climate change, including but not limited to:
- Changes in the distribution and prevalence of vector-borne diseases;
- Impacts on mental health and well-being;
- Effects on air quality and respiratory health;
- The influence of extreme weather events on public health.
The report must be publicly accessible and recognized by the CDC as comprehensive in its coverage of climate change's health impacts. In the absence of a single comprehensive report, a series of publications by the CDC that collectively cover the criteria above will also satisfy the resolution criteria. The resolution will rely on official CDC announcements or publications. In the event that the CDC has not published such a report by the specified date, the question will resolve as No.

